        <h3>Why predict menopause?</h3>
        <p>The cessation of a woman's reproductive life span is called menopause. Predicting it helps with planning around reproductive potential in infertility treatment, and with planning for premenopausal and postmenopausal health effects ahead of time rather than reacting to them.</p>

        <h3>What is the basis of prediction?</h3>
        <p>Unlike men, women are born with a finite number of follicles (germ cells), and the total number of follicles in the ovary is called ovarian reserve. It is the ovarian reserve, rather than age alone, that predicts menopause. Anti-Müllerian Hormone (AMH) has long been assessed in fertility clinics for diagnosing ovarian reserve in polycystic ovary syndrome and for IVF outcomes — its value declines with age and is found to be around 0.2 at menopause.</p>
        <p>e-healthwatch's Menopause Forecast uses a mathematical model built on two biomarkers: Anti-Müllerian Hormone (AMH) and Follicle Stimulating Hormone (FSH), measured on day three of the menstrual cycle, to predict the age of natural menopause onset.</p>
      </article>

